He will be the fourth President of the United States to receive it, but only the third who will be awarded the prize in the Committee itself.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan during the award.
The president does not want to avoid this subject because he is aware that he receives this prize by being a president who is leading a war in two countries at present.
He strengthened the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (about 1.1 million Euros).
It intends to donate to charitable works, but it has not yet specifically decided which ones.
His programme will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
