Czech discovery: a substance that works on "enduring" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the proliferation of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality in some cases takes over the fact that the combination does not act as intensively on the current variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at present.
However, it is possible to radically prolong the life of the sick through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption results in a series of side effects.
In addition, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of the experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are a mixture of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their links to the proteins of the virus.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiple-walled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, there would be no mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus will also be stopped in the patient's body, explaining the researchers in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
