The Chinese authorities have assigned the police the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous tendency for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some authorities have forced pregnant women of a second child to have abortions.
In addition, many couples have had selective abortions leading to an abnormally high ratio of boys and girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the policy of the single child.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already single children -- and in 2007 they softened a lot of their harsh slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, professor at the Institute of Population Research, at the University of Beijing, said that the central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced by copies of detailed regulations that have the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples, at their homes, and to drag prospectuses under their doors.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who wished to have more than one child.
According to the head of the family planning, the response was disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although those responsible in a rural city in the suburbs of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for couple files wishing for a second child after the launch of the campaign, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be approximately 165 000 -- slightly higher than 2009 but less than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of Family Planning Committee in the Municipality of Caolu of Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to provide their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years old and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26 years old, said that they would love to have two children and that they were legally authorized to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and the life insurance provided by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners wrongly consider that the policy of the single child is a problem of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose woman is pregnant seven months of the first child of the couple.
True, we're stealing the chance of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, Human Resources Manager, said she only wanted a single child because she was one herself. "We were the center of the family and used to be the one that everybody was taking care of us."
We don't usually take care of someone else and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company says it more quickly.
For couples working in two middle-class groups who lower the birth rate, he said, it is necessary to be selfish to succeed.
People aged 20 or 30 grew up seeing their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and don't want to have this lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even one child takes a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the space problems -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you need to write his or her CV to get a place in the best nursery."
Most of his friends are ready for this experience once, says Chen, but not two.
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, he says.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations Group has draft emission reduction plans
The climate conference, sponsored by the United Nations -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned under the banner of the Friday ramp, due to the publication of a document highlighting ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations most of the burden, in the near future.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases highlighted the remaining obstacles, as well as the path to be taken.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from all over the world coming to Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by a United Nations ad hoc working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give the poor to support climate warming in the long run and in the long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that managers would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General described on UN climate change, Yvo de Boer, as "the complete image".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020 from 25 to 45 per cent compared to the 1990 levels, while the main developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 50 per cent to 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations have occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, United States Representative for Climate Negotiation, rejected any discussion that required the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if they were not funded by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration becomes more harsh to China than the Bush administration was, two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, says Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, He Yafei stated that the US main negotiator was "no sense", or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not help China financially to combat climate warming.
With the future economic paths of the major world powers at stake, defects have appeared both in the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations while the poorest nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers were fighting to know who should suffer the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their efforts to make the major issuers responsible for their actions.
This is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also climate advisor to Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say that negotiations will lead to a minimum, political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, has drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Arthur Runge-Metzger, Head of the European Commission's climate unit, said that the action of small island States has "put political pressure on the complete political process", in part by what they are now unified and that they ask emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, while delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the issues before the Heads of Government reached agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Minister of Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister descended from their aircraft and rushed to the Bella Center building to attend closed meetings and briefings, in order to be able to make claims that will be considered during the following week.
The true image of the gathering -- in which 13,000 people come in and out of the Congress Palace every day -- guitar-player activists present night shows mocking countries that they think are betraying themselves and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity only increases: almost all important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of governments will be in Copenhagen.
We enter the courtyard of the grandes, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice-President for World Conservation International Policy.
The heavy weights are coming.
