Manageria revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the great French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies to its employees has been a reminder of the position of the companies to consumers prior to the marketing revolution: it is a matter of having employees adhere to "values" determined from above, as it once was, to impose on consumers products thought of by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has handed over market conquer strategies to the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preferences factors comes back regularly!
A demobilisation of employees can result in a mortifying demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects particularly managers.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that authoritarian management revenues are totally against.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would be to put the employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Are internal opinion surveys – like the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – going to encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally comes, after many deviations, to do priority... what it has always done.!
- Then, because of authoritarianism—one of the diseases of power—increases in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
In the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, through intellectual comfort, the old Behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "nerosciences" and widely disseminated, to their own, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leaves" (sic) of the engagement of managers, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr comforts leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, which is inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, implies adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is possible only if it appears clearly as a means of realizing some of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, only the studies from the Reasoning Analysis adopt this design of employees' motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business based on a predetermined dose that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilisation factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and restore their "local" human resources management.
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
