Turkish justice dissolves the pro-Kurdian party, heavy decision of consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court declared on Friday the dissolution of the country's main pro-kurd party, a decision that was immediately followed by anger demonstrations in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the government's task, which has just reached the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "flight of activities detrimental to the independence of the State and its indivisible unity", the president of the Hasim Kiliç Court declared to the press at the end of four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified seven-vote majority was required to pronounce the dissolution, said Mr.Kiliç, adding that 37 of the party's executives, including President Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity from Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Party's Treasury of property.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
His leaders had warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without a label.
The decision follows a procedure initiated in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered to be a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that DTP is the legal political showcase of PKK rebels.
The party claims, however, that it has "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court's verdict comes as the government has just held hands with the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, to try to delay the support of the Kurds to the PKK and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP had claimed that dissolution could lead to an increase in tensions in South East Anatolian, where numerous demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As of the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the largest city in the south-east populated by the majority of Kurds.
Order forces fired tear grenades and used water cannons, while protesters launched molotov cocktails or stones, with frogs.
About a hundred people also showed up in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr.Türk stated that the Justice decision would "deepen despair".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurde, ndlr) by banning a party, he said to the press.
The Government, formed by a party from the Islamic movement, also deplored the decision.
We are in principle opposed to the closure of the parties.
That resolves nothing, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total torpedoes of the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
Of course, one can expect a PKK reaction, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
