They were born with dinosaurs.
The Tawa Hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long for 1.50m high, its posterior limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was filled with sharp and curving teeth, its short arms ended with scarf claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt reports from the University of Texas in Austin and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa Hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the land that emerged from the supercontinent, the Pangea and was heading towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa sheds light on a new day the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the relationship, the distribution and the characteristics of the kinships.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt began searching with other paleontologists on the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irris of the Utah Natural History Museum and a member of the search team tells that sometimes they could find a dozen bones in one day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The searches updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories regarding the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa according to the word of the Hopi Indians for the god of the sun.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: the dinosaur fossils from Trias are extremely rare and are limited to some incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, however it states that it allows to confirm certain theories regarding the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth approximately 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify all the first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, when the swarfs have been divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaur and the velociraptor that later appeared and descended from birds, sauropods, long neck quadrupeds, and those that are related to them and ornithischians herbivores, including species such as triceratops and stegosaur.
According to the studies by S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species presents an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers found clues that the Tawa Hallae had small air sacs in his skull-level bones, as well as birds that are the offspring of the the theropods.
These small air pockets facilitate the breathing of birds compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air bags in its bones.
Since the apparent line of the vast sauropods also had air bags and a light bone, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive migration waves to North America.
Since the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, researchers concluded that the sarians appeared there.
As a result, the three major lines of evolution have divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all the emerging lands that formed the Pangée Supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the Paleontologist team has also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot come down from a common ancestor that would have migrated, advancing researchers.
Alan Turner of the Museum of Natural History of New York and co-author of the journal Science Studies says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
Of course there are some contradictions.
Martin Sander, paleontologist in Bonn says there is an even older species, the silesaure, which lived in present Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong vision because in South America there are a large number of dinosaur fossils that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how did dinosaurs become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary age while coming from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, still remains a mystery today.
At the time of Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of the current crocodiles and many other Syrians.
At the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread across the planet, thus promoting the development of many new species, while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassics.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There could have been a massive extinction in which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or, then, dinosaurs were better suited and they were thus able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favourable to the development of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and which since then had vegetated in the shadow: these were mammals.
