75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased over the past few years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Federality and Professional Career of Women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey, conducted in 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have experienced limited careers due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in couples and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing people into marriage and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after they have settled in a couple, which is 4.1 for those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with a stable job have needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which has led them to push the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the starting date of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that increases the age gap in the marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who did elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"An additional distinction is also found among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have completed elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have done intermediate or higher education reverse this program and give priority to achieving stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
